data: {"created":"2026-03-11T17:01:19.24473725Z","hasMore":true,"id":"msg_012rm1hctshns29a1K1HvLgD","items":[{"hasMore":false,"id":"msg_012rm1hctshns29a1K1HvLgD-0","partial":true,"text":"---\n\n## USâChina Trade War Briefing\n\n### Confirmed facts (2+ sources)\n\nOn April 2, 2025, the Trump administration unveiled \"Liberation Day\" tariffs, imposing a baseline 10% tariff on all imports and an additional 34% on Chinese goods, which escalated rapidly â US tariffs on China peaked at 145% before a mutual de-escalation on May 12, 2025 brought them down to 30% (on top of existing Section 301 and sectoral tariffs), while China reduced its retaliatory tariffs from 125% to 10% (confirmed by CSIS, China Briefing, AP News search snippet, and the Reuters/WEF timeline summaries). On October 30, 2025, Trump and Xi met in Busan, South Korea, and struck a further trade truce: the US reduced the \"fentanyl\" tariff from 20% to 10% and extended the lower reciprocal tariff rate for another year, with China adjusting countermeasures in return (confirmed by China Briefing, CNBC, and Reuters search snippet). In February 2026, the US Supreme Court struck down tariffs imposed under the IEEPA (International Emergency Economic Powers Act), eliminating the fentanyl and reciprocal tariffs; Trump responded by announcing a temporary 10-15% global tariff under a separate statute requiring Congressional approval to extend (confirmed by China Briefing, AP News, and CFR search snippet). Despite US tariffs, China's goods trade surplus surpassed $1 trillion for the first time in November 2025, as Chinese exporters diverted trade flows through Southeast Asia, Mexico, and other markets (confirmed by CNBC and corroborated by Guardian/PIIE search data showing average US tariffs on Chinese imports reaching 58% by late September 2025).\n\n### Conflicting or single-source claims\n\nCNBC characterizes 2025 as a clear strategic win for China, arguing Beijing's retaliation and export diversification amounted to \"a master class in economic statecraft\" â this framing is not echoed by other sources, which take a more neutral tone. CSIS uniquely argues that the US emerged from the escalation-de-escalation cycle with a *lower* effective tariff rate than it had on the morning of April 2, undermining the administration's credibility on \"out-escalation.\" The exact current trade-weighted average tariff on China varies by source: PIIE's search snippet cites 47.5% (as of its last update), the Guardian cites 58% (as of September 2025), and China Briefing/Global Trade Alert cites 29.7% after the Supreme Court ruling and 15% global tariff â these reflect different points in time and different methodologies, not necessarily contradictions, but the range is wide.\n\n### Key data points\n\n- **145% â 30%**: Peak US tariff on China (April 2025) reduced to 30% on May 12, 2025 (plus existing Section 301/232 tariffs).\n- **125% â 10%**: China's retaliatory tariff on US goods reduced in the May 12 de-escalation.\n- **$1 trillion+**: China's goods trade surplus as of November 2025 â a record.\n- **~40% decline**: Estimated year-on-year drop in Chinese exports to the US in Q3 2025, offset by gains to Asia, Europe, Mexico, and the Middle East.\n- **$300 billion/year**: Estimated reduction in US real income by 2028 from tariffs, per research cited by CSIS.\n- **~30%**: Effective tariff rate on many Chinese goods as of February 2026 after the Supreme Court ruling, per China Briefing/Global Trade Alert (trade-weighted average: 29.7%).\n- **February 20, 2026**: US Supreme Court strikes down IEEPA-based tariffs; Trump announces replacement 10-15% global tariff requiring Congressional renewal after 150 days.\n- **October 30, 2025**: Trump-Xi meeting in Busan, South Korea â fentanyl tariff halved to 10%, reciprocal tariff extension agreed.\n- **Section 232 tariffs at 50%**: Steel, aluminum, and semi-finished copper products face the highest sectoral rates.\n\n### Note on sources\n\n**Successfully fetched and read (4 sources):**\n1. AP News â Supreme Court tariff ruling and US-China trade uncertainty: https://apnews.com/article/tariffs-china-trump-trade-supreme-court-fb8d38ae3664e845199d13113d03b471\n2. CSIS â \"Understanding the Temporary De-Escalation of the U.S.-China Trade War\" (May 13, 2025): https://www.csis.org/analysis/understanding-temporary-de-escalation-us-china-trade-war\n3. China Briefing â \"US-China Tariff Rates - What Are They Now?\" (updated Feb 2026): https://www.china-briefing.com/news/us-china-tariff-rates-2025\n4. CNBC â \"China won the 2025 battle in Trump's trade war\" (Dec 31, 2025): https://www.cnbc.com/2025/12/31/trump-china-trade-war-tariffs.html\n\n**Failed to fetch (2 sources):** PIIE chart page and Reuters timeline both returned timeout errors. Their search snippets were still used for cross-referencing data points (PIIE: 47.5% average US tariff; Reuters: October 30 truce details).\n\n**Search results also referenced** (used for cross-referencing via snippets): The Guardian, WEF, CFR, CNN, SCMP, and others.","type":"text"},{"arguments":"{\"todos\": [{\"activeForm\":\"Connecting to DuckDuckGo MCP server\",\"content\":\"Connect to DuckDuckGo MCP server\",\"status\":\"completed\"},{\"activeForm\":\"Running DuckDuckGo searches\",\"content\":\"Phase 1: Run up to 5 DuckDuckGo searches\",\"status\":\"completed\"},{\"activeForm\":\"Selecting URLs for deep reading\",\"content\":\"Phase 2: Select up to 6 URLs for deep reading\",\"status\":\"completed\"},{\"activeForm\":\"Fetching content from selected URLs\",\"content\":\"Phase 3: Fetch content from selected URLs\",\"status\":\"completed\"},{\"activeForm\":\"Cross-referencing findings\",\"content\":\"Phase 4: Cross-reference findings\",\"status\":\"completed\"},{\"activeForm\":\"Writing final briefing report\",\"content\":\"Phase 5: Write final briefing report\",\"status\":\"completed\"}]}","callID":"toolu_011ncvg2KyGjXegMfCynWcjS","id":"msg_012rm1hctshns29a1K1HvLgD-1","name":"todoWrite","output":{"content":[{"text":"Todo list updated:\n\n[\n  {\n    \"content\": \"Connect to DuckDuckGo MCP server\",\n    \"status\": \"completed\",\n    \"activeForm\": \"Connecting to DuckDuckGo MCP server\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"content\": \"Phase 1: Run up to 5 DuckDuckGo searches\",\n    \"status\": \"completed\",\n    \"activeForm\": \"Running DuckDuckGo searches\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"content\": \"Phase 2: Select up to 6 URLs for deep reading\",\n    \"status\": \"completed\",\n    \"activeForm\": \"Selecting URLs for deep reading\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"content\": \"Phase 3: Fetch content from selected URLs\",\n    \"status\": \"completed\",\n    \"activeForm\": \"Fetching content from selected URLs\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"content\": \"Phase 4: Cross-reference findings\",\n    \"status\": \"completed\",\n    \"activeForm\": \"Cross-referencing findings\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"content\": \"Phase 5: Write final briefing report\",\n    \"status\": \"completed\",\n    \"activeForm\": \"Writing final briefing report\"\n  }\n]","type":"text"}]},"partial":true,"type":"tool"}],"role":"assistant"}

