data: {"created":"2026-03-11T18:12:28.944141625Z","hasMore":true,"id":"msg_01YUy7ogWyXNrxGDLKURWHPJ","items":[{"hasMore":false,"id":"msg_01YUy7ogWyXNrxGDLKURWHPJ-0","partial":true,"text":"The grep is returning files but no line numbers. Let me search for the 2025 section content directly.","type":"text"},{"arguments":"{\"-n\": true, \"output_mode\": \"content\", \"path\": \"/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt\", \"pattern\": \"February 2025|April 2025|May 12|145%|Liberation Day\", \"-C\": 3}","callID":"toolu_01HLcvSa6JsKQ3UWbshXBafw","id":"msg_01YUy7ogWyXNrxGDLKURWHPJ-1","name":"grep","output":{"content":[{"text":"/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:215:2025 marked a significant escalation of the conflict under the [second Trump administration](/wiki/Second_presidency_of_Donald_Trump \"Second presidency of Donald Trump\"). A series of [increasing tariffs](/wiki/Tariffs_in_the_second_Trump_administration \"Tariffs in the second Trump administration\") led to the U.S. imposing a 145% tariff on Chinese goods, and China imposing a 125% tariff on American goods in response; these measures are forecast to cause a 0.2% loss of global merchandise trade.[\\[15\\]](#cite_note-15)[\\[16\\]](#cite_note-16)[\\[17\\]](#cite_note-:12-17) Despite this, both countries have excluded certain items from their tariff lists and continue to try and find a resolution to the trade war.[\\[18\\]](#cite_note-18)[\\[19\\]](#cite_note-reuters.com-19)\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:618:On April 2, 2025, the United States imposed a 34% duty on Chinese imports as part of his [Liberation Day tariffs](/wiki/Liberation_Day_tariffs \"Liberation Day tariffs\"), which applied on top of the 20% \"fentanyl tariff\" and other prior measures.[\\[105\\]](#cite_note-105) China responded by imposing a matching tariff of 34% on all American goods, suspending negotiations regarding [the sale of TikTok](/wiki/Restrictions_on_TikTok_in_the_United_States \"Restrictions on TikTok in the United States\") and restricting exports of six [heavy rare-earths](/wiki/Rare-earth_element \"Rare-earth element\") and [rare-earth magnets](/wiki/Rare-earth_magnet \"Rare-earth magnet\").[\\[106\\]](#cite_note-106)[\\[107\\]](#cite_note-:21-107) Trump responded by raising tariffs by an additional 50% beginning April 9, bringing the baseline tariff on Chinese imports to 104%.[\\[108\\]](#cite_note-108)[\\[109\\]](#cite_note-109) China responded with a matching tariff of 50%, bringing its baseline tariff on American goods to 84%.[\\[110\\]](#cite_note-110) The US then raised its tariffs to 145%, and China responded by raising its tariffs to 125%.[\\[111\\]](#cite_note-111) On May 12, both countries reached a truce in a bid to reduce tensions. The U.S. reduced tariffs on Chinese goods to 30% while China responded by reducing tariffs on U.S. products to 10%.[\\[112\\]](#cite_note-ReutersSlash-112)\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:748:- May 12: The Chinese government announced exemptions for tariffs on 79 additional US goods.[\\[255\\]](#cite_note-trade_war_turns_two_SCMP-255)\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:808:- April 2: Trump raised the tariffs on China by another 34%, after accusing China of tariff and non-tariff trade barriers of 67% as part of his reciprocal tariffs policy, expressed during his [\"Liberation Day\" speech](/wiki/Donald_Trump%27s_Liberation_Day_speech \"Donald Trump's Liberation Day speech\").[\\[288\\]](#cite_note-288)[\\[289\\]](#cite_note-289) The White House confirmed tariffs would stack on top of previous impositions, resulting in an effective tariff rate of 54% on all Chinese imports to the US beginning in one week.[\\[290\\]](#cite_note-Doherty-290)\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:811:- April 9: China responded with retaliatory tariffs of 84% on US goods.[\\[293\\]](#cite_note-293) In response, Trump increased tariffs on Chinese goods to 125% on the same day. However, the White House clarified the next day that the tariff rate had risen to 145%.[\\[17\\]](#cite_note-:12-17)\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:823:- May 12: The United States and China reach an agreement to reduce tariffs in an effort to de-escalate trade tensions. The U.S. agreed to cut tariffs on Chinese goods to 30%, while China reciprocated with tariff reductions on U.S. products to 10%. Both sides agreed to assess the situation after 90 days.[\\[112\\]](#cite_note-ReutersSlash-112) The agreement was preceded by talks between senior U.S. and Chinese officials side the day before in [Switzerland](/wiki/Switzerland \"Switzerland\").[\\[299\\]](#cite_note-299)\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:991:This section needs to be **updated**. The reason given is: **Lacking in post-2020 information, especially in reactions to the Trump administration's escalation in 2025**. Please help update this article to reflect recent events or newly available information. *(April 2025)*\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:1226:017. ^ [***a***](#cite_ref-:12_17-0) [***b***](#cite_ref-:12_17-1) Iordache, Dan Mangan, Kevin Breuninger, Christina Wilkie, Megan Cassella, Jesse Pound, Ruxandra (April 10, 2025). [\"Trump tariffs on China now total 145%, White House clarifies: Live updates\"](https://www.cnbc.com/2025/04/10/china-trump-tariffs-live-updates.html). *CNBC*.`{{cite news}}`: CS1 maint: multiple names: authors list ([link](/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_multiple_names:_authors_list \"Category:CS1 maint: multiple names: authors list\"))\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:1302:085. ^ [***a***](#cite_ref-:20_85-0) [***b***](#cite_ref-:20_85-1) Wong, Kandy (April 3, 2025). [\"Explainer: After Trump's 'Liberation Day', what's China's effective tariff rate?\"](https://www.scmp.com/economy/global-economy/article/3305013/dust-settles-trumps-liberation-day-whats-chinas-effective-tariff-rate). *South China Morning Post*. Retrieved April 5, 2025.\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:1329:112. ^ [***a***](#cite_ref-ReutersSlash_112-0) [***b***](#cite_ref-ReutersSlash_112-1) [\"US and China Reach Agreement to Slash Tariffs\"](https://www.reuters.com/world/china/us-china-reach-deal-slash-tariffs-officials-say-2025-05-12). Reuters. Retrieved May 12, 2025.\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:1353:136. [**^**](#cite_ref-136) Tan, Huileng; Mody, Seema (April 4, 2018). [\"China's ambassador to the US explains why the country is striking back\"](https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/03/chinese-ambassador-to-us-we-will-take-measures-to-fight-back-very-soon.html). [*CNBC*](/wiki/CNBC \"CNBC\"). [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20190513200911/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/03/chinese-ambassador-to-us-we-will-take-measures-to-fight-back-very-soon.html) from the original on May 13, 2019. Retrieved May 12, 2019.\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:1404:187. [**^**](#cite_ref-187) Bryan, Bob (January 3, 2019). [\"Trump says the Treasury is taking in 'MANY billions of dollars' from the tariffs on China. The only problem is that US companies are paying the price\"](https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-who-pays-for-tariffs-trade-war-costs-2019-1). [*Business Insider*](/wiki/Business_Insider \"Business Insider\"). [Archived](https://web.archive.org/web/20190511233858/https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-who-pays-for-tariffs-trade-war-costs-2019-1) from the original on May 11, 2019. Retrieved May 12, 2019.\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:3192:  - [Liberation Day tariffs](/wiki/Liberation_Day_tariffs \"Liberation Day tariffs\")\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:3277:  - [First Putin call](/wiki/February_2025_Putin%E2%80%93Trump_phone_call \"February 2025 PutinâTrump phone call\")\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:3278:  - [Saudi Arabia meeting](/wiki/February_2025_United_States%E2%80%93Russia_meeting_in_Saudi_Arabia \"February 2025 United StatesâRussia meeting in Saudi Arabia\")\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:3477:    - [Day of Action](/wiki/50501_protests_in_April_2025 \"50501 protests in April 2025\")\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:4378:- [Use American English from April 2025](/wiki/Category:Use_American_English_from_April_2025 \"Category:Use American English from April 2025\")\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd0-e55583084d49/truncated-outputs/webFetch-toolu_01TcGM3w7GGqRV6TJqMAbW5A.txt:4380:- [Use mdy dates from April 2025](/wiki/Category:Use_mdy_dates_from_April_2025 \"Category:Use mdy dates from April 2025\")\n/home/nanobot/sessions/65b2a187-f291-4135-bbd