data: {"created":"2026-03-11T18:12:50.846120003Z","hasMore":true,"id":"msg_017J842wR5C6NPidA61cxUfL","items":[{"hasMore":false,"id":"msg_017J842wR5C6NPidA61cxUfL-0","partial":true,"text":"## US--China Trade War Briefing\n\n### Confirmed facts (2+ sources)\n\nThe US--China trade war began in January 2018 when President Trump imposed tariffs on Chinese goods, citing unfair trade practices and intellectual property theft; China retaliated with its own tariffs, and the conflict has escalated through multiple administrations (confirmed by all three sources). In 2025, the second Trump administration dramatically escalated tariffs using IEEPA authority -- peaking at 145% on Chinese goods, with China responding at 125% -- before both sides reached a May 12, 2025 truce reducing rates to 30% (US) and 10% (China) for a 90-day assessment period (Wikipedia and Tax Foundation both confirm this sequence). The Biden administration kept Trump-era tariffs in place and added new levies on EVs, solar panels, and semiconductor-related exports, maintaining the effective rate at ~20% throughout his term (Wikipedia and Tax Foundation). American consumers and businesses bear the cost of tariffs through higher prices -- the average effective tariff rate hit 7.7% in 2025, the highest since 1947 (Tax Foundation), consistent with Wikipedia's reporting that intermediate goods prices rose 10-30% matching tariff levels.\n\n### Conflicting or single-source claims\n\nThe Tax Foundation reports that in February 2026, the US Supreme Court struck down the IEEPA tariffs in a 6-3 decision (*Learning Resources Inc. v. Trump*), after which Trump pivoted to Section 122 authority with a 10% tariff on all countries -- Wikipedia corroborates the ruling but the detailed Section 122 pivot and its household cost estimates ($200-$600 per household) come solely from Tax Foundation's modeling. Wikipedia (single source) reports that at the October 2025 APEC summit in Busan, Trump and Xi agreed to reduce fentanyl tariffs by 10% and China suspended rare earth export restrictions for one year, but this is not confirmed in the other sources reviewed. The Tax Foundation's estimate that the 2025 tariffs cost the average US household $1,000 is a modeled figure not independently verified by the other sources.\n\n### Key data points\n\n- **Peak tariff rates (April 2025):** US imposed 145% on Chinese goods; China imposed 125% on US goods.\n- **May 12, 2025 truce:** US reduced to 30%, China to 10%, with a 90-day review window.\n- **Effective tariff rate:** Rose from 2.4% in 2024 to 7.7% in 2025 -- highest since 1947 (Tax Foundation).\n- **Customs revenue:** $264 billion collected in calendar year 2025, up from $79 billion in 2024 (Tax Foundation).\n- **Trade deficit:** Barely changed -- fell only $2.1 billion in 2025; the goods deficit actually increased by $25.5 billion year-over-year (Tax Foundation).\n- **Job losses:** Moody's estimated 300,000 US jobs lost or not created by August 2019; Oxford Economics estimated 245,000 jobs lost from first-term tariffs (Wikipedia).\n- **US farmer impact:** Agricultural exports to China fell from $19.4B (2017) to $9.1B (2018); soybean farmers lost an estimated $24 billion in exports (Wikipedia).\n- **Supply chain shifts:** 244 manufacturer relocation decisions tracked (2018-2023), with Vietnam the top destination (75 of 244 moves); only 15.6% were true reshoring to the US (Wikipedia).\n- **China's response:** Reduced US oil imports by 90%, stopped buying US soybeans (shifting to Brazil/Argentina), and cut US Treasury holdings to $756.3B -- lowest since March 2009 (Wikipedia).\n- **Supreme Court (Feb 2026):** IEEPA tariffs ruled unconstitutional in 6-3 decision (Wikipedia, Tax Foundation).\n\n### Note on sources\n\nThree sources were successfully loaded and cross-referenced:\n\n1. **Wikipedia** -- \"China--United States trade war\" (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/China%E2%80%93United_States_trade_war) -- fetched via webFetch. Comprehensive chronology through late 2025/early 2026.\n2. **Tax Foundation** -- \"Tariff Tracker: Impact of Trump Tariffs \u0026 Trade War by the Numbers\" (https://taxfoundation.org/research/all/federal/trump-tariffs-trade-war/) -- fetched via DuckDuckGo MCP `fetch_content`. Detailed quantitative analysis including revenue, GDP, and household cost modeling through February 2026.\n3. **BBC News** -- \"A quick guide to the US-China trade war\" (https://www.bbc.com/news/business-45899310) -- fetched via DuckDuckGo MCP `fetch_content`. Shorter overview focused on the 2018-2020 period.\n\n**Failed fetches:** Reuters, CFR, Brookings, PIIE, Investopedia, and NYT all failed due to either `httpx.TimeoutError` bugs in the MCP server or 403 blocks. DuckDuckGo search returned 0 results across all 7 queries attempted (bot detection). The fallback URL strategy provided sufficient source diversity for cross-referencing.","type":"text"}],"role":"assistant"}

